# AGENTS.md — ApliDocs schema-v2 cohort index

This directory publishes one read-only SQLite/FTS5 index for
<CORPUS_DESCRIPTION>.

The query interpreter must use SQLite 3.53.3 or newer; ApliDocs rejects older
providers before opening this FTS5 index.

- Authorized reader cohort: <COHORT_DESCRIPTION>
- Access policy: `<ACCESS_POLICY_ID>`
- Included roots: <AUTHORIZED_ROOTS>
- Excluded/pruned directories: <EXCLUDED_DIRS>
- Scheduled rebuild: <REBUILD_TIME>

## Security boundary

This database has no per-row ACL. Any reader can retrieve every included path
and all included extracted text, including through `sql`. The administrator has
therefore built it only from roots that every member of <COHORT_DESCRIPTION> may
read.

Do not give this database to anybody outside that cohort. Do not infer or try to
reconstruct material outside <AUTHORIZED_ROOTS> or inside <EXCLUDED_DIRS> from
its absence. The source filesystem, not this index, is authoritative.

## Always run `status` first

Run `status` before trusting search results. If `generated_at` is more than two
days old, the scheduled build is failing: report the stale timestamp and verify
important claims against the source filesystem.

The schema-v2 `meta` table also records the corpus UUID, policy ID/generation,
authorized roots and `excluded_access_count`. A successful fail-closed build must
publish that count as zero. Treat a non-zero value as an invalid/legacy index and
flag it; current builders abort instead of publishing permission-denied omissions.

## Access ladder

1. Recommended, over SSH:

       ssh <NAS_USER>@nas '<WRAPPER_PATH> status'
       ssh <NAS_USER>@nas '<WRAPPER_PATH> search "quarterly report" --year 2024'

   Use the full wrapper path because non-interactive SSH may not load `~/bin`
   into `PATH`.

2. From a mounted SMB share, use a local Python and the read-only CLI:

       python "<SMB_PATH>\cli\aplidocs_cli.py" --db "<SMB_PATH>\aplidocs-index.sqlite" status

   Windows mapped drives and direct UNC paths (`\\server\share\...`) are
   supported. The builder is POSIX-only; Windows is a query client. Prepare the
   client venv as documented in README (the audited setup pins
   `cysqlite==0.3.4`) and run its SQLite-version/FTS5 probe first.

3. Without the CLI, copy the database to a private local temporary and use a
   compatible SQLite/FTS5 tool. If it must be opened directly over SMB, use a
   correctly percent-encoded SQLite file URI with `mode=ro&immutable=1`.

## CLI contract

JSON is the default output. `--tsv` requests tab-separated rows.

| Command | Result |
|---|---|
| `status` | Freshness and core build metadata. Always run first. |
| `search "terms"` | Fused name/path and body-text results with match source and optional snippet. |
| `name "terms"` | Filename/path FTS only. |
| `sql "SELECT ..."` | One bounded, read-only `SELECT`, `WITH` or `EXPLAIN` statement; requires a provider with `setlimit`/`getlimit`/progress-handler support. |

`search` and `name` support `--area`, `--ext`, `--year`, `--metadata-only` and a
`--limit` is bounded from 1 to 1000; an overly broad combined search may also
ask for more terms/filters rather than approximate RRF beyond its candidate cap.
Only final hits receive metadata/snippets. On providers without all three
required capabilities (`Connection.setlimit`, `getlimit` and a progress
handler such as stdlib `set_progress_handler` or cysqlite `progress`), `sql`
intentionally exits 3; use the other commands or ask the administrator for a
compatible provider. Do not bypass a cohort wrapper with
`--db`; current wrappers reject that argument. Source ACLs
do not filter rows in the index: the publication-directory/database ACL is the
effective read boundary, while the source remains authoritative for document
facts.

Examples:

    <WRAPPER_PATH> search "ACME contract" --limit 5
    <WRAPPER_PATH> search "Q3 budget" --ext xlsx
    <WRAPPER_PATH> name "meeting notes" --year 2025
    <WRAPPER_PATH> sql "SELECT relpath FROM files WHERE path_year = 2023 ORDER BY relpath"

To inspect policy/build state not shown by a particular CLI version:

    <WRAPPER_PATH> sql "SELECT generated_at, file_count, corpus_uuid, access_policy_id, access_policy_generation, access_roots, excluded_access_count FROM meta"

## Minimal schema v2

- `meta` has one row: schema/tool version, UTC generation time, elapsed time,
  file/content counts and status JSON, `corpus_root`, `corpus_uuid`,
  `access_policy_id`, `access_policy_generation`, `policy_digest`, serialized
  `access_roots` and `excluded_access_count`.
- `files` has one row per included file. `relpath` and `filename` preserve exact
  on-disk spelling; `relpath_nfc` and `filename_nfc` are normalized search
  forms. Other useful columns include `area` (`.` for a file loose at corpus
  root), lowercase `ext`, size, `mtime`/`mtime_ns`/`ctime_ns`, device/inode,
  `source_hash`, `path_year`, optional `name_meta`, `metadata_only` and
  `content_status`.
- `content` has extracted `text`, `extractor` and strong `source_sig`, keyed by
  exact `relpath`.
- `files_fts` searches normalized filename/path; `content_fts` searches body
  text. Both use FTS5 `unicode61 remove_diacritics 2`.

`content_status` is one of `extracted`, `empty_pdf`, `unsupported_format`,
`metadata_only`, `too_big`, `error` or `no_text_type`. `metadata_only` still
reveals the file's name/path; it only suppresses body extraction.

Confirm the live schema when needed:

    <WRAPPER_PATH> sql "SELECT name, sql FROM sqlite_master WHERE type='table' ORDER BY name"

## Read-only rules

- Never write, modify, replace or delete anything in `<PUBLISH_DIR>`.
- The builder atomically replaces the SQLite file on every successful rebuild;
  do not keep a long-lived connection and assume it will see a later version.
- Trust `name_meta` and path-derived fields only as hints. Verify decisive facts
  against an authorized source document.
- Never widen access to the database on the theory that original DSM ACLs will
  filter results. They do not apply inside this index.
